# Gate
  `ruins_visits++`
  > The watchtower gate leans open between two stones carved like sleeping dogs.
  > Their muzzles are worn smooth by rain, but their eyes remain sharp, watching the road behind you instead of the ruin ahead.
  > `lantern_lit` Your lantern paints warm teeth along the archway stones. The dark beyond the gate retreats one careful inch.
  + `!lantern_lit && !heard_bell_rumor` *-> [Continue](#.LoseNerve)
  + -> [Continue](#.Approach)

## LoseNerve
  > The darkness beneath the arch presses against your face until you step back gasping.
  > For a moment you are certain the tower is breathing, and that it has mistaken you for something it once swallowed.
  + -> [Return to the village](/main.saga#Village)

## Approach
  > Your lantern throws gold over a stair spiraling down under the tower.
  > The steps are slick but unworn. No one has used them in years, or else everyone who used them learned to leave no mark.
  + -> [Descend into the courtyard](#Courtyard)
  + -> [Search the gatehouse](#.Gatehouse)
  + -> [Return to Brindlewick](/main.saga#Village)

### Gatehouse
  `found_chalk ?= false`
  > The gatehouse roof has collapsed, but a dry shelf remains beneath a slab of slate.
  > Old watch rosters have melted into gray pulp. A mug sits upright in the dust, full of rain that never reached it.
  + *-> [Take the white chalk](#.TakeChalk)
  + -> [Return to the gate](#..)

#### TakeChalk
  `found_chalk := true`
  > You pocket a stick of white chalk. It leaves a moon-pale smear on your thumb.
  > The smear does not wash away when rain touches it. If anything, it brightens.
  + -> [Continue](#Gate.Approach)

# Courtyard
  > The sunken courtyard lies open to the rain. Four doors wait under four broken arches.
  > Grass grows between the stones in thin, colorless blades. The place feels less abandoned than paused.
  > `found_chalk` The chalk in your pocket leaves a pale crescent on your fingertips whenever you touch it.
  + -> [Inspect the well](#.Well)
  + -> [Enter the archive](#.Archive)
  + `old_key` -> [Try the lower door](#.LowerDoor)
  + `!old_key` -> [Examine the sealed lower door](#.SealedDoor)
  + -> [Retreat to the gate](#Gate)

## Well
  `well_echo = rand(100)`
  > You lean over the well. Far below, water repeats your breathing.
  > The echo is almost faithful, but not quite. It exhales half a beat after you stop.
  + `well_echo > 70` *-> [Continue](#.CoinGlimmer)
  + -> [Continue](#.QuietWater)

### CoinGlimmer
  `coin := coin + 1`
  > Something bright spins up from the dark, lands at your feet, and becomes a coin.
  > It is dry. It is warm. The face stamped on it has been scratched away.
  + -> [Continue](#..QuietWater)

### QuietWater
  > The well gives nothing back but the small sound of rain.
  > Still, when you step away, your reflection lingers at the rim for one second too long.
  + -> [Continue](#Courtyard)

## Archive
  > Shelves of stone tablets lean against the walls. Most are blank with age.
  > The air tastes of limestone dust and sealed rooms. Your footsteps come back to you from the wrong corners.
  > `knows_mark` You keep searching for a bell inside a closed eye, the shape Blue Scarf pressed into your thoughts like a thumbprint.
  + `knows_mark` -> [Look for the archivist's mark](#.MarkedTablet)
  + -> [Search randomly](#.RandomTablet)
  + -> [Return to the courtyard](#Courtyard)

### MarkedTablet
  `archive_mark := true`
  > You find the bell-in-eye mark on a tablet tucked behind three blank stones.
  > When you knock twice, a hidden drawer opens with a sigh of old air and powdered bronze.
  + *-> [Take the bronze tongue](#.BronzeTongue)
  + -> [Leave the drawer alone](#..)

#### BronzeTongue
  `bronze_tongue := true`
  > The bronze tongue is cold and heavy, made for a bell that should not still exist.
  > It vibrates once in your hand, a silent note you feel in your teeth.
  + -> [Continue](#Courtyard.Archive)

### RandomTablet
  `dust_count++`
  > Dust coats your hands. The tablets say nothing you understand.
  > You find lists of names, then lists of bells, then a list where every name has been carefully chiseled away.
  + `dust_count < 3` -> [Keep searching](#.)
  + -> [Give up](#..)

## SealedDoor
  > The lower door has no handle, only a keyhole shaped like a crooked tooth.
  > Rain runs down its face and parts around the keyhole, refusing to enter.
  + -> [Return to the courtyard](#Courtyard)

## LowerDoor
  > The blackened key turns with a sound like a cough.
  > `lower_door_hint` You remember the locksmith's warning and work slowly, letting oil and patience do what force would ruin.
  + `lower_door_hint && lantern_lit` *-> [Continue](#.OiledLock)
  + -> [Continue](#.StubbornLock)

### StubbornLock
  > The lock resists you. Rust flakes fall like old scabs.
  > Something on the other side shifts closer, then thinks better of it.
  + -> [Return to the courtyard](#Courtyard)

### OiledLock
  > The lock remembers the key. The lower door opens inward.
  > The stair beyond is dry, and the air rising from it smells faintly of metal, rainless stone, and old thunder.
  + -> [Enter the bell chamber](/bell.saga#Chamber)
